This paper is about machine learning and specifically addresses the problem of overfitting. The proposed approach, marginalized corrupted features (MCF), is a regularization technique that can be applied to a range of predictors and corruption models. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). However, given that the paper focuses on developing predictors that generalize well to test data, cs.LG and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories. The use of empirical evaluations on a variety of data sets also suggests that cs.CV and cs.DS are possible sub-categories. Finally, the mention of robustness to feature deletion at test time suggests that cs.CR is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
